# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alutiiq-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The **Achumawi language** (also **Achomawi** or **Pit River language**) is the indigenous language spoken by the Pit River people in the northeast corner of present-day California.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The term Achumawi is an anglicization of the name of the Fall River band, *ajúmmááwí*, from *ajúmmá* 'river'.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Originally there were nine bands, with dialect differences primarily between upriver (Atwamwi, Astariwawi; Kosalektawi, Hammawi, Hewisedawi dialects) and downriver (Madesiwi, Itsatawi, Ilmawi, and Achumawi (proper) dialects), demarcated by the Big Valley mountains east of the Fall River valley.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Together, Achumawi and Atsugewi are said to comprise the Palaihnihan language family separate from the adjacent and related Shastan family.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The basis of this grouping is weakened by poor quality of data.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] David Olmsted's data dictionary depends almost entirely upon de Angulo, and carelessly includes Pomo vocabulary from a manuscript in which he (de Angulo) set out to demonstrate that Achumawi and Pomo are not related.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] William Bright and Shirley Silver questioned Olmsted's results and methods of reconstruction.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The phenomenon of non-reciprocal intelligibility is a matter of bilingualism in the smaller and more dependent of two exogamous communities; Kroeber (1925:308) estimated that the Achumawi were ten times more numerous than the Atsugewi.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The stops and affricate (aside from the marginally contrastive glottal stop) are in three series, plain, aspirated, and laryngealized or glottalized.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The aspirated series is contrastive only syllable-initially and probably derives historically from the voiceless-released first member of a consonant cluster, as in the neighboring Yana language.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The plain-aspirated distinction is neutralized and realized with voiceless release in syllable-final position and before another consonant; the aspirates are much more fortis than this voiceless release.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Syllable-initial plain stops are voiceless (without voiceless release) after long vowel or when geminate (long), and voiced elsewhere.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The laryngealized stops are similar in articulation to the ejective glottalized stops of neighboring languages, but more lenis, that is, not "popped" unless an unusual effort is made at articulating the distinction.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The language has a 5-vowel system /i e a o u/.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Two degrees of length are contrastive for both vowels and consonants.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Long vowels are typically more peripheral and short vowels more centralized, phonetically [ɪ ɛ ʌ ə ʊ].
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The mid vowels /e o/ are probably of secondary origin historically, as in Yana and Atsugewi.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] A short centralized vowel [ə ɨ] appears epenthetically between the consonants of certain prefixes, as in *lhúpta* "let's go!".
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Vowel length assimilates the next successive laryngeal state, that is, the second mora of a long vowel is devoiced before a plain or aspirated consonant (preaspiration) and word finally before silence, and is laryngealized before a laryngealized consonant.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] In upriver dialects vowels and plain stops are more fully voiced.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] In downriver dialects, utterance-final syllables may be devoiced or whispered, especially under interrogative intonation.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] A light syllable consists of a consonant and vowel (CV), and a heavy syllable either contains a long vowel (CVˑ) or is closed with a second consonant (CVC).
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Unlike the neighboring and related language Atsugewi, Achumawi has contrastive high and low tones.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The Achumawi language does not have gender but it has two forms of the copula ("to be") distinguishing animate and inanimate.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The verb stem comprises one or more verb roots plus optional adverbial affixes.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Inflectional affixes on verbs distinguish singular, dual, and plural number, and suffixes may optionally express severality and plurality of nouns.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Many nouns and adjectives are derived from verb stems or participles, and some verb stems are formed by noun incorporation.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] The language has independent adjectives and numerals.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Today, the Achumawi language is extinct.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] Out of an estimated 1500 Achumawi people remaining in northeastern California, perhaps ten spoke the language in 1991, with only eight in 2000.
[src:alutiiq-language/achumawi-language] As of 2013, a mobile app was planned for the language.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] An **affricate** is a consonant that begins as a stop and releases as a fricative, generally with the same place of articulation (most often coronal).
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] It is often difficult to decide if a stop and fricative form a single phoneme or a consonant pair.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] English has two affricate phonemes, /t͡ʃ/ and /d͡ʒ/, generally spelled *ch* and *j*, respectively.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] However, voiced affricates other than [d͡ʒ] are relatively uncommon.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] For several places of articulation they are not attested at all.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Much less common are labiodental affricates, such as [p͡f] in German, Kinyarwanda and Izi, or velar affricates, such as [k͡x] in Tswana (written *kg*) or in High Alemannic Swiss German dialects.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Worldwide, relatively few languages have affricates in these positions even though the corresponding stop consonants, [p] and [k], are common or virtually universal.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Also less common are alveolar affricates where the fricative release is lateral, such as the [t͡ɬ] sound found in Nahuatl and Navajo.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Some other Athabaskan languages, such as Dene Suline, have unaspirated, aspirated, and ejective series of affricates whose release may be dental, alveolar, postalveolar, or lateral: [t̪͡θ], [t̪͡θʰ], [t̪͡θʼ], [t͡s], [t͡sʰ], [t͡sʼ], [t͡ʃ], [t͡ʃʰ], [t͡ʃʼ], [t͡ɬ], [t͡ɬʰ], and [t͡ɬʼ].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Affricates are transcribed in the International Phonetic Alphabet by a combination of two letters, one for the stop element and the other for the fricative element.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In order to clarify that these form a single consonant, a tie bar may be used.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] The tie bar appears most commonly above the two letters, but may be placed under them if it fits better there, or simply because it is more legible.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] This is derived from the IPA convention of indicating other releases with a superscript.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] However, this convention is more typically used for a fricated release that is too brief to be considered a true affricate.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Ligatures ⟨, , , /, ⟩ for the non-coronal affricates [pɸ] [bβ], [pf] [bv], [cç] [ɟʝ], [kx] [ɡɣ]/[gɣ], [qχ] [ɢʁ] have also been used.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Any of these notations can be used to distinguish an affricate from a sequence of plosive plus fricative, which is contrastive in languages such as Polish.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] However, in languages where there is no such distinction within a syllable, such as English or Turkish, a simple sequence of letters such as ⟨tʃ⟩ is commonly used, with no overt indication that they form an affricate.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In such cases the syllable boundary may be written to distinguish the plosive-fricative sequence in *petshop* /ˈpɛt.ʃɒp/ from the similar affricate in *ketchup* /ˈkɛtʃʌp/.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In other phonetic transcription systems, such as the Americanist system, affricates may be transcribed with single letters.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Single letters may also be used with phonemic transcription in IPA: [tʃ] and [dʒ] are sometimes transcribed with the symbols for the palatal stops, ⟨c⟩ and ⟨ɟ⟩, for example in the IPA *Handbook*.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] The exact phonetic difference varies between languages.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In stop–fricative sequences, the stop has a release burst before the fricative starts; but in affricates, the fricative element *is* the release.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Phonologically, stop–fricative sequences may have a syllable boundary between the two segments, but not necessarily.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In English, /ts/ and /dz/ (*nuts*, *nods*) are considered phonemically stop–fricative sequences.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] They often contain a morpheme boundary (for example, *nuts* = *nut* + *s*).
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] The English affricate phonemes /t͡ʃ/ and /d͡ʒ/ do not contain morpheme boundaries.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] The /t/ in 'worst shin' can be elided: [wɜː(ɹ)sʃɪn].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Stop–fricatives can be distinguished acoustically from affricates by the rise time of the frication noise, which is shorter for affricates.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] When affricates are geminated, it is the duration of the plosive closure that is lengthened, not that of the frication.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] For example, /t͜sː/ is pronounced [tːs], not *[tsː].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Polish has been reported to favour phonological gemination through rearticulation of the affricate, rather than the common method of lengthening the plosive closure.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In the case of coronals, the symbols ⟨t, d⟩ are normally used for the stop portion of the affricate regardless of place.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] For example, ⟨t͡ʂ⟩ is commonly seen for ⟨ʈ͡ʂ⟩, ⟨t͡ʃ⟩ for ⟨t̠͡ʃ⟩ and ⟨t͡θ⟩ for ⟨t̪͡θ⟩.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] The exemplar languages are ones that have been reported to have these sounds, but in several cases, they may need confirmation.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] The Northwest Caucasian languages Abkhaz and Ubykh both contrast sibilant affricates at four places of articulation: alveolar, postalveolar, alveolo-palatal and retroflex.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] They also distinguish voiceless, voiced, and ejective affricates at each of these.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] When a language has only one type of affricate, it is usually a sibilant; this is the case in e.g.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Arabic ([d̠ʒ]), most dialects of Spanish ([t̠ʃ]), and Thai ([tɕ]).
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Itene, Oro Win, Sangtam, and Wari' have a dental stop with bilabial trilled release [t̪ʙ̥].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Although most affricates are homorganic, Navajo and Chiricahua Apache have a heterorganic alveolar-velar affricate [tx].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Itene, Oro Win, Sangtam, and Wari' have a voiceless dental bilabially trilled affricate [t̪ʙ̥] (see Trilled affricate).
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Other heterorganic affricates are reported for Northern Sotho and other Bantu languages such as Phuthi, which has alveolar–labiodental affricates [tf] and [dv], and Sesotho, which has bilabial–palatoalveolar affricates [pʃ] and [bʒ].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] The coronal and dorsal places of articulation attested as ejectives as well: [tθʼ, tsʼ, tɬʼ, tʃʼ, tɕʼ, tʂʼ, c𝼆ʼ, kxʼ, k𝼄ʼ, qχʼ].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Several Khoisan languages such as Taa are reported to have voiced ejective affricates, but these are actually *pre*-voiced: [dtsʼ, dtʃʼ].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Affricates are also commonly aspirated: [ɱp̪fʰ, tθʰ, tsʰ, tɬʰ, tʃʰ, tɕʰ, tʂʰ], murmured: [ɱb̪vʱ, dðʱ, dzʱ, dɮʱ, dʒʱ, dʑʱ, dʐʱ], and prenasalized: [ⁿdz, ⁿtsʰ, ᶯɖʐ, ᶯʈʂʰ] (as in Hmong).
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Labialized, palatalized, velarized, and pharyngealized affricates are also common.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Affricates may also have phonemic length, that is, affected by a chroneme, as in Italian and Karelian.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In phonology, affricates tend to behave similarly to stops, taking part in phonological patterns that fricatives do not.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Kehrein (2002) analyzes phonetic affricates as phonological stops.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] A sibilant or lateral (and presumably trilled) stop can be realized phonetically only as an affricate and so might be analyzed phonemically as a sibilant or lateral stop.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In that analysis, affricates other than sibilants and laterals are a phonetic mechanism for distinguishing stops at similar places of articulation (like more than one labial, coronal, or dorsal place).
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] For example, Chipewyan has laminal dental [t̪͡θ] vs. apical alveolar [t]; other languages may contrast velar [k] with palatal [c͡ç] and uvular [q͡χ].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Affricates may also be a strategy to increase the phonetic contrast between aspirated or ejective and tenuis consonants.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] According to Kehrein (2002), no language contrasts a non-sibilant, non-lateral affricate with a stop at the same place of articulation and with the same phonation and airstream mechanism, such as /t̪/ and /t̪θ/ or /k/ and /kx/.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In feature-based phonology, affricates are distinguished from stops by the feature [+delayed release].
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Affrication (sometimes called *affricatization*) is a sound change by which a consonant, usually a stop or fricative, changes into an affricate.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] In rare instances, a fricative–stop contour may occur.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] This is the case in dialects of Scottish Gaelic that have velar frication [ˣ] where other dialects have pre-aspiration.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] For example, in the Harris dialect there is *seachd* [ʃaˣkʰ] 'seven' and *ochd* [ɔˣkʰ] 'eight' (or [ʃax͜kʰ], [ɔx͜kʰ]).
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Richard Wiese argues this is the case for word-initial fricative-plosive sequences in German, and coined the term **suffricate** for such contours.
[src:alutiiq-language/affricate-consonant] Awngi has 2 suffricates /s͡t/ and /ʃ͡t/ according to some analyses.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] The dense spruce forests of Afognak Island are home to Kodiak bears, Roosevelt elk, and Sitka black-tailed deer.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] Many people visit the island recreationally for hunting and fishing.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] The United States Census of 1890 noted a series of settlements along the beachline near the Alutiiq village of *Ag’waneq*, including Rutkovsky village, inhabited by a group of retired employees of the Russian-American Company.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] Ag’waneq was abandoned after the 1964 Good Friday earthquake devastated the island.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] The descendants of the Alaska Native inhabitants of the island are officially recognized as the Native Village of Afognak.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] Most of them now live in Port Lions or Kodiak.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] In the early 21st century, there are a few small logging camps and fishing lodges on the island.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] A community of Russian Old Believers live at Aleneva.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] The economy is based on subsistence and logging.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] Transportation is provided by float plane from Kodiak to various areas around the island.
[src:alutiiq-language/afognak-island] The 2000 census reported a population of 169 persons.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The broad topic of the English language, in its diverse forms, as used by Black people in North America has various names, including **Black American English** or simply **Black English**.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Also common is the somewhat controversial term **Ebonics** and, more recently in academic linguistics, **African-American Language** (**AAL**).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] African-American English began as early as the 17th century, when the Atlantic slave trade brought enslaved West Africans into Southern colonies (which eventually became the Southern United States in the late 18th century).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] During the development of plantation culture in this region, nonstandard dialects of English were widely spoken by British settlers, which probably resulted in both first- and second-language English varieties being developed by African Americans.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The 19th century's evolving cotton-plantation industry, and eventually the 20th century's Great Migration, certainly contributed greatly to the spread of the first of these varieties as stable dialects of English among African Americans.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The most widespread modern dialect is known as African-American Vernacular English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] For example, features of AAVE grammar such as complex verb tenses and zero copula (omitting forms of the verb 'be') may have been inherited from African languages such as Hausa.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] AAVE shares several linguistic features with Southern White Vernacular English (and even more with older Southern dialects).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Furthermore, the farm tenancy system that replaced slavery in the American South drew in Southern Whites, leading to a context for an interracial speech relationship dynamic among socioeconomic equals throughout the South and leading to many shared features until the start of WWII.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] In this case, changes that became robust after the 1930s most strongly mark ethnic distinctions in speech.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) is the native variety of the majority of working-class and many middle-class African Americans, particularly in urban areas, with its own unique accent, grammar, and vocabulary features.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] AAVE is often used by middle-class African Americans in casual, intimate, and informal settings as one end of a sociocultural language continuum, and AAVE shows some slight variations by region or city.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] African-American Standard English is the prestigious and native end of the middle-class African-American English continuum that is used for more formal or public settings and in more careful speech than is AAVE.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The term has been largely popularized by linguist Arthur Spears.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] This variety exhibits standard English vocabulary and grammar but often retains certain elements of the unique AAVE accent, with intonational or rhythmic features maintained more than phonological ones.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Frequently, middle-class African Americans are bi-dialectal between this standard variety and AAVE, tending toward using the former variety in school and other public places, so that adults will frequently even codeswitch between the two varieties within a single conversation.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The phonological features maintained in this standard dialect tend to be less marked.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] For instance, one such characteristic is the omission of the final consonant in word-final consonant clusters, so words such as *past* or *hand* may lose their final consonant sound.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Black Appalachian Americans have been reported as increasingly adopting Appalachian/Southern dialect commonly associated with White Appalachians.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] These similarities include an accent that is rhotic, the categorical use of the grammatical construction in "he works" and "she goes" (rather than the AAVE "he work" and "she go"), and Appalachian vocabulary (such as *airish* for "windy").
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] However, even African-American English in Appalachia is diverse, with African-American women linguistically divided along sociocultural lines.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Despite its distinctiveness, AAAE shares many features with other varieties of Appalachian English, including the use of nonstandard pronunciation, grammar, and vocabulary.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] AAAE also shares features with other varieties of African-American English, particularly those spoken in the South.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] For instance, a study of African-American communities in the Appalachian region of Virginia found that the dialects of these communities shared many features with both African-American English and Southern White English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] African-American English in the North Carolina Outer Banks is rapidly accommodating to urban AAVE through the recent generations, despite having aligned with local Outer Banks English for centuries.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The dialect has been studied by linguists and has been documented in various works, such as the book *African American Outer Banks English: A Sociolinguistic Study* by Elizabeth C.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] This book provides a detailed description of the language, including its grammar, vocabulary, and pronunciation.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] It also provides a history of the dialect and examines how it has changed over time.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] African Nova Scotian English (ANS) is spoken by descendants of Black Nova Scotians, Black immigrants from the United States who live in Nova Scotia, Canada.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Though most African-American freedom seekers in Canada ended up in Ontario through the Underground Railroad, only the dialect of African Nova Scotians retains the influence of West African Pidgin English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] In the 19th century, African Nova Scotian English would have been indistinguishable from English spoken in Jamaica or Suriname.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] However, it has been increasingly de-creolized since this time, due to interaction and influence from the White Nova Scotian population.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Desegregation of the province's school boards in 1964 further accelerated the process of de-creolization.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The language is a relative of the African-American Vernacular English, with significant variations unique to the group's history in the area.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] There are noted differences in the dialects of those from Guysborough County (Black Loyalists) and those from North Preston (Black Refugees), the Guysborough group having been in the province three generations earlier.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Howe & Walker (2000) use data from early recordings of African Nova Scotian English, Samaná English, and the recordings of former slaves to demonstrate that speech patterns were inherited from nonstandard colonial English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The dialect was extensively studied in 1992 by Shana Poplack and Sali Tagliamonte from the University of Ottawa.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The grammar of ANS is largely based on standard English, but there are several distinct features that set it apart from other varieties of English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] These features include the use of the negative concord—which is the use of multiple negative words in a sentence to emphasize the negative—and the double negative, which is the use of two negative words in a sentence to express a positive meaning.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] In addition, ANS also has its own pronunciation rules, such as *Th*-stopping (pronouncing ⫽ð⫽, usually spelled ⟨th⟩, as [d]) and *G*-dropping (pronouncing ⫽ɪŋ⫽, spelled ⟨-ing⟩, as [ɪn], [ɨ̞n] or [ən]).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] A commonality between African Nova Scotian English and African-American Vernacular English is *r*-deletion.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] This rate of deletion is 57% among Black Nova Scotians, and 60% among African Americans in Philadelphia.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Meanwhile, in the surrounding mostly white communities of Nova Scotia, *r*-deletion does not occur.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Sea Island Creole English, or Gullah, is the distinct language of some African Americans along the South Carolina and Georgia coast and extending slightly into North Carolina and Florida.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Gullah is an English creole: a natural language grammatically independent from English that uses mostly English vocabulary.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Most Gullah speakers today are probably bidialectal.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] A sub-dialect of Gullah is also spoken in Oklahoma and Texas, known as Afro-Seminole Creole.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The language is derived from a mixture of African languages and English, with words and phrases from Caribbean and West African languages such as Akan, Wolof, and Fula.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Gullah has been described as a "linguistic bridge between Africa and the New World".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The Gullah culture is deeply rooted in African traditions, particularly in the practice of storytelling and the use of handicrafts.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Gullahs have a strong connection to the land, and their traditional fishing, farming, and basket-weaving practices reflect this.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] In recent years, efforts have been made to preserve Gullah culture and language.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The Gullah Geechee Cultural Heritage Corridor Commission was established in 2006 to help protect and promote the Gullah culture.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The commission has partnered with universities, museums, and other organizations to develop programs and initiatives to preserve Gullah language and traditions.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] There is a long tradition of representing the distinctive speech of African Americans in American literature.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] A number of researchers have looked into the ways that American authors have depicted the speech of Black characters, investigating how Black identity is established and how it connects to other characters.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Brasch (1981:x) argues that early mass media portrayals of Black speech are the strongest historical evidence of a separate variety of English for Black people.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Early popular works are also used to determine the similarities that historical varieties of Black speech have in common with modern AAVE.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The earliest depictions of Black speech came from works written in the 18th century, primarily by white authors.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] A notable exception is *Clotel* (1853), the first novel written by an African American (William Wells Brown).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Depictions have largely been restricted to dialogue and the first novel written entirely in AAVE was June Jordan's *His Own Where* (1971), though Alice Walker's epistolary novel *The Color Purple* (1982) is a much more widely known work written entirely in AAVE.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Lorraine Hansberry's 1959 play *A Raisin in the Sun* also has near exclusive use of AAVE.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The poetry of Langston Hughes (1901–1967) uses AAVE extensively.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] As there is no established spelling system for AAVE, depicting it in literature is instead often done through spelling changes to indicate its phonological features, or to contribute to the impression that AAVE is being used (eye dialect).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] More recently, authors have begun focusing on grammatical cues, and even the use of certain rhetorical strategies.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Portrayals of Black characters in film and television are also done with varying degrees of authenticity.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The speech and behavioral patterns of Delilah Johnson from *Imitation of Life* (1934) are reminiscent of minstrel performances that set out to exaggerate stereotypes rather than depict Black speech authentically.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] African-American English has been used in television and film since the early days of Hollywood.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] For example, in the 1940s, the popular radio show Amos 'n' Andy featured African-American characters who spoke in African-American English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] This show was popular and influential, and it established AAE as a part of popular culture.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] In the decades since, AAE has continued to be used in television and film as a way to depict African-American characters.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] It is often used to provide comedic relief or to illustrate the unique characteristics of African-American culture.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] For example, the 1990s television show *Martin* featured a main character who speaks in AAE and is often the source of comedic moments.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Nonstandard African-American varieties of English have been stereotypically associated with a lower level of education and low social status.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Since the 1960s, however, linguists have demonstrated that each of these varieties, and namely African-American Vernacular English, is a "legitimate, rule-governed, and fully developed dialect".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The techniques used to improve the proficiency of African-American students learning standard written English have sometimes been similar to that of teaching a second language.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Contrastive analysis is used for teaching topics in African-American Vernacular English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Both the phonological and syntactic features of a student's speech can be analyzed and recorded in order to identify points for contrast with Standard American English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Another way AAE can be taught is based on a strategy, communicative flexibility, that focuses on language used at home and analyzes speech during dramatic play.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Using this method, children are taught to recognize when SAE is being used and in which occasions, rather than conforming to the speech around them in order to sound correct.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Although the stigmatization of AAE has continued, AAE remains because it has functioned as a social identity marker for many African-Americans.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] The goal with teaching SAE is not to end its use, but to help students differentiate between settings where its use is and is not considered acceptable.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] In addition, research has also found that AAE can be used as a bridge to mainstream academic English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] By understanding the similarities and differences between AAE and mainstream American English, teachers can provide students with effective strategies for learning and using both dialects.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] Recently, linguists like John McWhorter have tried to persuade the public that "Black English" is not a separate language from or imperfect form of "Standard English".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] He argues that Black English is a separate dialect, distinct from Standard English in the same way that Canadian French and Swiss French are distinct from the standard dialect of Parisian French.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] He also acknowledges that we have a long way to go as a society in recognizing Black English as anything but "full of slang and bad grammar".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] African-American English, particularly AAVE, is often used by rappers in hip-hop music.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-english] AAE also has a long tradition as the main dialect of spirituals, blues, jazz, R&B, and other music movements and styles originating with African Americans.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] However, a minority of linguists argue that the vernacular shares so many characteristics with African creole languages spoken around the world that it could have originated as a creole (or semi-creole) language, distinct from the English language, before re-converging with English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) may be considered a dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] While it is clear that there is a strong historical relationship between AAVE and earlier Southern U.S. dialects, the origins of AAVE are still a matter of debate.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The presiding theory among linguists is that AAVE has always been a dialect of English, meaning that it originated from earlier English dialects rather than from English-based creole languages that "decreolized" back into English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Linguist John McWhorter maintains that the contribution of West African languages to AAVE is minimal.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] According to this theory, these captives first developed pidgins or simplified mixtures of languages.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Because pidgins form from close contact between speakers of different languages, the slave trade would have been exactly such a situation.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Creolist John Dillard quotes, for example, slave ship captain William Smith describing the sheer diversity of mutually unintelligible languages just in The Gambia.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] By 1715, an African pidgin was reproduced in novels by Daniel Defoe, in particular, *The Life of Colonel Jacque*.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] In 1721, Cotton Mather conducted the first attempt at recording the speech of slaves in his interviews regarding the practice of smallpox inoculation.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] By the time of the American Revolution, varieties among slave creoles were not quite mutually intelligible.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The abolitionist papers before the war form a rich corpus of examples of plantation creole.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] In *Army Life in a Black Regiment* (1870), Thomas Wentworth Higginson detailed many features of his African-American soldiers' language.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Opponents of the creole theory suggest that such pidgins or creoles existed but simply died out without directly contributing to modern AAVE.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Many pronunciation features set AAVE apart from other forms of American English (particularly General American).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] John McWhorter argues that what truly unites all AAVE accents is a uniquely wide-ranging intonation pattern or "melody", which characterizes even the most "neutral" or light African-American accent.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] A handful of multisyllabic words in AAVE differ from General American in their stress placement so that, for example, *police*, *guitar*, and *Detroit* are pronounced with initial stress instead of ultimate stress.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The following are phonological differences in AAVE vowel and consonant sounds.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Final consonant groups or clusters in AAVE have been examined as evidence of the systematic nature of this language variety, governed by specific rules.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] These analyses have been utilized to bolster arguments concerning the historical origins of AAVE.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Consonant cluster reduction is a phonological process where a final consonant group or cluster, consisting of two adjacent consonant sounds, is simplified or reduced to a single consonant sound.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The analysis of consonant cluster reduction in AAVE assumes that, initially, final clusters are present and intact in the language.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] For example, the word "tes" in AAVE originates from "test", with the final "t" of the "st" consonant cluster being deleted in word-final position.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] McWhorter discusses an accent continuum from "a 'deep' Black English through a 'light' Black English to standard English," saying the sounds on this continuum may vary from one African American speaker to the next or even in a single speaker from one situational context to the next.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Although AAVE does not necessarily have the simple past-tense marker of other English varieties (that is, the *-ed* of "work*ed*"), it does have an optional tense system with at least four aspects of the past tense and two aspects of the future tense.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The dialect uses several tense–aspect–mood markers integrated into the predicate phrase, including *gon* or *gonna* (future tense), *done* (completive aspect), *be* (habitual aspect, state of being), and *been* (durative aspect).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] These can function separately or in conjunction.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] means "he finished work a long time ago".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] means "until recently, he worked over a long period of time".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The latter example shows one of the most distinctive features of AAVE: the use of *be* to indicate that performance of the verb is of a habitual nature.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] In most other American English dialects, this can only be expressed unambiguously by using adverbs such as *usually*.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] This aspect-marking form of *been* or BIN is stressed and semantically distinct from the unstressed form: *She BIN running* ('She has been running for a long time') and *She been running* ('She has been running').
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] This aspect has been given several names, including *perfect phase*, *remote past*, and *remote phase* (this article uses the third).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] As shown above, *been* places action in the distant past.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] However, when *been* is used with stative verbs or gerund forms, *been* shows that the action began in the distant past and that it is continuing now.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Rickford (1999) suggests that a better translation when used with stative verbs is "for a long time".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] For instance, in response to "I like your new dress", one might hear *Oh, I been had this dress*, meaning that the speaker has had the dress for a long time and that it isn't new.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] means "I bought her clothes a long time ago".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] means "I've been buying her clothes for a long time".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Auxiliaries in African American Vernacular English are related in a typical pattern.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] They can be grouped into negative forms and affirmative forms for each of the words.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] For example, "had" is an affirmative form, while "hatn" is the corresponding negative form.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] These same auxiliaries can be used to mark sentences for the anterior aspect.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] As another example, *was* marks type 1 sentences, which by default are present tense, and transforms them to a time before the present.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Take, for instance, "She at home": the word *was* can be inserted to mark this sentence, making the marked equivalent "She was at home".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Auxiliaries such as these also have opposing negative and affirmative forms.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] In its negative form the auxiliary verb "wadn" is used to convey the opposing affirmative form.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The irrealis mood marker *be*, having no intrinsic tense refers to a current or future event that may be less than real.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The dialect uses double modals, such as *might could*, which can function in various ways, including as adverbs.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] While AAVE shares these with Creole languages, early recordings of African Nova Scotian English, Samaná English, and recordings of former slaves indicate that negation was likely inherited from nonstandard colonial English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] AAVE shares most of its lexicon with other varieties of English, particularly that of informal and Southern dialects, such as, the relatively recent use of *y'all*.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The main sources for new words are combining, shifting, shortening, blending, borrowing, and creating.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] It has also been suggested that some of the vocabulary unique to AAVE has its origin in West African languages.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] However, etymology is often difficult to trace and, without a trail of recorded usage, these proposed origins cannot be considered proven.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Early AAVE and Gullah contributed a number of words of African origin to the American English mainstream, including *gumbo*, *goober*, *yam*, and *banjo*.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Compounding in AAVE is a very common method in creating new vocabulary.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The most common type of compounding is the noun–noun combination, followed by adjective–noun combination.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] AAVE also combines adjectives with other adjectives less frequently, but more often than in standard American English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] AAVE has also contributed slang expressions such as *cool* and *hip*, *to dig*, *jazz*, *tote*, and *bad-mouth*, a calque from Mandinka.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] In many cases, the proposed West African etymologies are not recognized by linguists or the *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Innovative African American slang is often formed by combining, shifting, shortening, blending, and borrowing English words and phrases that are regarded as informal.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] AAVE also has words that either are not found in other American English dialects or that have strikingly different meanings.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] For example, there are several words in AAVE referring to White people that are not part of mainstream American English; these include *gray* as an adjective for Whites (as in *gray dude*), possibly from the color of Confederate uniforms; and *paddy*, an extension of the slang use for "Irish".
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] "Red bone" is another example of this, usually referring to light-skinned African Americans.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] "Ofay", which is pejorative, is another general term for a White person; it might derive from the Ibibio word *afia*, which means "light-colored", from the Yoruba word *ofe*, spoken in hopes of disappearing from danger.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] However, most dictionaries simply say its etymology is unknown.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] AAVE has also contributed many words and phrases to other varieties of English, including *chill out*, *main squeeze*, *soul*, *funky*, and *threads*.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] African-American Vernacular English has influenced the development of other dialects of English.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The AAVE accent, New York accent, and Spanish-language accents have together yielded the sound of New York Latino English, some of whose speakers use an accent indistinguishable from an AAVE one.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] AAVE has also influenced certain Chicano accents and Liberian Settler English, directly derived from the AAVE of the original 16,000 African Americans who migrated to Liberia in the 1800s.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] In the United States, urban youth participating in hip-hop culture or marginalized as ethnic minorities may also adopt AAVE, or prominent elements of it: for example, Southeast-Asian Americans embracing hip-hop identities.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Internet slang has borrowed heavily from AAVE, which has often been characterized as cultural appropriation.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The term *blaccent* broadly refers to the accent associated with AAVE, but more often refers to the use of AAVE by non-African American speakers.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Early research on African-American Vernacular English took place in cities such as New York, Los Angeles, and Chicago.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] These studies concluded that AAVE was linguistically homogenous, or spoken roughly the same way everywhere around the country.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Later sociolinguists found that these cities lacked the influence of the rural South and that earlier studies had not considered the representation of the Southern United States.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] While AAVE began as mostly rural and Southern, today it is mostly urban and nationally widespread.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Its more recent urban features are now diffusing back into rural areas.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Urban AAVE alone is intensifying with the grammatical features exemplified in these sentences: "He be the best" (intensified equative *be*), "She be done had her baby" (resultative *be done*), and "They come hollerin" (indignant *come*).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] On the other hand, rural AAVE alone shows certain features too, such as: "I was a-huntin" (*a*-prefixing); "It riz above us" (different irregular forms); and "I want for to eat it" (*for to* complement).
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Use of the word *bees* in place of *be* to mean *is* or *are* in standard English, as in the sentence "That's the way it bees", is one of the rarest of all deep AAVE features today.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Most middle-class AAVE speakers would recognize the verb *bees* as part of only a deep "Southern" or "country" speaker's vocabulary.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] There are at least 10 distinct regional accents in AAVE.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Memphis, Atlanta, and Research Triangle AAVE incorporates the dress vowel raising and face vowel lowering associated with white Southern accents.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Louis AAVE are developing, since the mid-twentieth century, an iconic merger of the vowels in square and nurse, making *there* sound like *thurr*.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Californian AAVE often lacks a cot–caught merger, especially before nasals.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Regional patterns of pronunciation and word choice are also apparent on social media.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] There is general uniformity of AAVE grammar, despite its vast geographic spread across the whole country.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] This may be due in part to relatively recent migrations of some African Americans out of the American South (see Great Migration and Second Great Migration) as well as to long-term racial segregation that kept these speakers living together in largely homogeneous communities.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] African-American Vernacular suffers from persistent stigma and negative social evaluation in American culture.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] By definition, as a vernacular dialect of English, AAVE has not received the social prestige of a standard dialect, leading to widespread and long-standing misconceptions that it is a grammatically inferior form of English, which linguistics research of the twentieth century has debunked.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Some of the harshest criticism of AAVE or its use has come from African Americans themselves.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] A conspicuous example was the "Pound Cake speech", in which Bill Cosby criticized fellow African Americans for various social behaviors, including the way they talked.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Educators traditionally have attempted to eliminate AAVE usage through the public education system, perceiving the dialect as grammatically defective.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] In 1974, the teacher-led Conference on College Composition and Communication issued a position statement affirming students' rights to their own dialects and the validity of all dialects.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Mainstream linguistics has long agreed with this view about dialects.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] This program lasted three years and then died off.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Many notable genres, styles, and movements within African-American music, and cultural and artistic movements or subcultures, are offshoots of African-American culture.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] The genres of Christian spirituals, blues, jazz, R&B, and hip-hop all originated from Black Americans.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] AAVE, thus, is the typical dialect employed in their lyrics, often even among these genres' non-Black musicians.
[src:alutiiq-language/african-american-vernacular-english] Two such cultural movements with particular international prominence are jazz culture of the late 1930s and 1940s (with its associated AAVE slang, jive talk) and hip-hop culture of the late 20th century into the present.
[src:alutiiq-language/afro-seminole-creole] Afro-Seminole Creole was first identified in 1978 by Ian Hancock, a linguist at the University of Texas.
[src:alutiiq-language/afro-seminole-creole] Before that, no one in the academic world was aware of its existence.
[src:alutiiq-language/afro-seminole-creole] ASC arose when enslaved Gullah speakers from the South Carolina and Georgia coastal region, later called "Black Seminoles", escaped from slavery on rice plantations and fled into the Florida wilderness.
[src:alutiiq-language/afro-seminole-creole] This process began in the late 1600s, and continued into the 1830s.
[src:alutiiq-language/afro-seminole-creole] In Florida, the Black Seminoles built their own independent communities, but established a close partnership with the Seminole Indians.
[src:alutiiq-language/afro-seminole-creole] That alliance helped protect both groups during the First and Second Seminole Wars.
[src:alutiiq-language/afro-seminole-creole] The present-day speakers of Afro-Seminole Creole live in Seminole County, Oklahoma and Brackettville, Texas in the United States, and in Nacimiento de los Negros, Coahuila, Mexico.
[src:alutiiq-language/afro-seminole-creole] ASC is threatened with extinction as there are only about 200 native speakers today.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The Ahtna language consists of four different dialects: Upper, Central, Lower, and Western.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Three of the four are still spoken today.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The similar name Atnah occurs in the journals of Simon Fraser and other early European diarists in what is now British Columbia as a reference to the Tsilhqot'in people, another Northern Athapaskan group.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Ahtna is classified as belonging to the Northern Athabaskan languages, a subgrouping of the Athabaskan languages.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Ahtna is one of the eleven Athabaskan languages native to Alaska.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The Ahtna language comes from the proto-Athabaskan language, believed to have evolved 5,000 to 10,000 years ago when humans migrated from Eurasia to North America over the Bering land bridge (Beringia), when it was dried up and exposed creating a natural land bridge.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Many indigenous Native American languages are thought to have derived from this proto-Athabaskan language.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Ahtna and other Athabaskan languages, like Navajo, have many similarities, due to their common ancestry.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The Ahtna language has changed very much and very often, and it is still changing today.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Within the past century more than one hundred words have made their way into the Ahtna vocabulary mostly due to influence from English.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Contact with Russians influenced the Ahtna language with many Russian loanwords being introduced.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] With contact from English speakers, especially recently, English words have also been introduced.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Some words are also borrowed from the Alaskan Tlingit and Alutiiq native languages.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The Ahtna region consists of the Copper River Basin and the Wrangell Mountains.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The Ahtna Region is bordered by the Nutzotin river in the Northeast and the Alaska Range in the North.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The Talkeetna Mountains are to the Chugach Mountains are to the South.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The Upper Ahtna live on the upper portion of the Copper River, The Middle or Central Ahtna live slightly down river from there, The Lower Ahtna live near the mouth of the Copper River, which opens into the Gulf of Alaska, and the Western Ahtna live to the West of the River.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The Ahtna people live on and near traditional villages.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] There are eight villages within the Ahtna Region: Cantwell, Chistochina, Chitina, Copper Center, Gakona, Gulkana, Mentasta and Tazlina.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] There are 15 elderly speakers out of a population of 500, and the language is facing extinction.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The subsistence and fishing-rights activist Katie John (1915–2013) of Mentasta helped develop an Ahtna alphabet in the 1970s and recorded a pronunciation guide of the Mentasta dialect.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] In 2012 a facing-bilingual collection of poetry in Ahtna and English, *The Indian Prophet*, was published by poet John Smelcer.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] In a revitalization program, the Ya Ne Dah Ah School in Sutton, Alaska teaches the Ahtna language as a part of its curriculum.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] As of 2010, a digital archiving project of Ahtna was underway.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] The vowels in Kari's practical orthography and phonology are as follows.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] There is some variation in pronunciation of words according to dialect.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Athabaskan languages are primarily prefixing.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] There is limited suffixation and often one word has as much meaning as an English language sentence.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Verbs are very complex therefore creating many different meanings or analysis of verbs.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Some verbs include syntactic principles in addition to and/or replacement of morphological principles when constructing a word.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] There are often six or more prefixes before the stem and then one or more suffixes.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] (1a) displays a surface form in Ahtna spelling while (1b) is the verb theme.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Three prefixes are present that have to be listed with the stem to make up the form.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Anything adjacent in a verb theme can be separated by morphemes in the forms surface.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Verb themes display what elements should be listed in a dictionary for a speaker to be able to reconstruct the verb.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] '#' displays an important word-internal boundary known as a disjunct boundary.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] In the Ahtna language the verb typically goes after the noun.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] In the Ahtna language, modifiers usually go after the noun they modify.
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] Examples of this include the name of the deity or trickster figure **Saghani Ggaay**, where **saghani** is the noun "raven" and **ggaay** the adjective "little, small" or in the term **nen ten** "permafrost", a combination of **nen** "land, ground" and **ten** "frozen".
[src:alutiiq-language/ahtna-language] This word order is also seen in place names such as **Dghelaay Ce'e** "Denali/Mount McKinley", literally "Biggest Mountain", and **Ben Ce'e** "Lake Susitna", literally "Big Lake".
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] The ethnonyms of the Sugpiaq-Alutiiq are a predicament.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] *Aleut*, *Alutiiq*, *Sugpiaq*, *Russian*, *Pacific Eskimo*, *Unegkuhmiut*, and *Chugach Eskimo* are among the terms that have been used to identify this group of Native people living on the Lower Kenai Peninsula of Alaska.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] About 400 of the Alutiiq population of 3,000 still speak the Alutiiq language.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] Alutiiq communities are currently in the process of revitalizing their language.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] In 2010 the high school in Kodiak responded to requests from students and agreed to teach the Alutiiq language.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] The Kodiak dialect of the language was spoken by only about 50 persons, all of them elderly, and the dialect was in danger of being lost entirely.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] As of 2014, Alaska Pacific University in Anchorage is offering classes using the "Where Are Your Keys?" technique.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] 2. [w] is an allophone of /ɣʷ/ syllable-finally and elsewhere.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] Two consecutive identical consonants are pronounced either separately or as a geminate depending on dialect.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] More consonants /ɾ~r, lʲ, rʲ/ are found in loanwords.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] All vowels except /ə/ are considered full vowels and can be either short or long. /ə/ does not lengthen and does not occur in vowel clusters but may tend to be devoiced as [ə̥] next to other consonants.
[src:alutiiq-language/alutiiq-language] After voiceless consonants, the voiceless nasals are written without h-.
